{{Infobox software |name = '''DeviceKit''' |logo = |screenshot = |caption = |collapsible = |author = |developer = David Zeuthen |released = 2008 |latest release version = 003 |latest release date = {{Start date and age|2009|03|02}}<ref>{{cite web | url=https://lists.freedesktop.org/archives/devkit-devel/2009-March/000123.html | title=DeviceKit 003 released | author=David Zeuthen | date=2009-03-02}}</ref> |latest preview version = |latest preview date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |programming language = |operating system = [[Linux]] |platform = |size = |language = |status = Deprecated |genre = [[Hardware abstraction layer|HAL]] |license = [[GNU General Public License|GPL]]<ref>{{cite web |url = http://hal.freedesktop.org/docs/DeviceKit/license.html |title = Appendix A. License |work = DeviceKit Reference Manual |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110817153630/http://hal.freedesktop.org/docs/DeviceKit/license.html |archivedate = 2011-08-17 |deadurl = yes |accessdate = 2017-01-15 |df = }}</ref> |website = [https://freedesktop.org/wiki/Software/DeviceKit/ freedesktop.org/wiki/Software/DeviceKit] }}
'''DeviceKit''' is a modular [[hardware abstraction layer]] designed for use in [[Linux]] systems that is designed to simplify device management and replace the current [[Monolithic kernel|monolithic]] Linux [[HAL (software)|HAL]]. DeviceKit includes the ability to enumerate system devices and send notifications when hardware is added or removed from the computer system.
In May 2008, HAL developer David Zeuthen announced his intention to deprecate HAL, mainly because of its complexity and redundancy with other libraries in the Linux environment.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://lists.freedesktop.org/archives/hal/2008-May/011560.html | title=Update on DeviceKit | author=David Zeuthen | date=2008-05-07 | accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> The only missing part in those libraries would be a centralized service to enumerate existing devices, signal adding/removal of devices and merging and classifying available hardware information in one point. DeviceKit is the new library providing those services, while the hardware is supposed to be accessed through other libraries instead of HAL or DeviceKit.
The first distribution to include DeviceKit was [[Fedora (operating system)|Fedora]] 11.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://fedoraproject.org/wiki/Features/DeviceKit | title=Features/DeviceKit | date=2010-03-29 | website=[[Fedora Project]] | accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref> [[Ubuntu (operating system)|Ubuntu]] 9.10 replaced some of the old HAL features with DeviceKit and functionality from [[udev]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://wiki.ubuntu.com/KarmicKoala/TechnicalOverview#hal_deprecation | title=TechnicalOverview: hal deprecation | website=ubuntu.com | date=2009-10-28 | accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref>
On 1 December 2009, it was announced that DeviceKit-disks was renamed to udisks and that a similar rename would happen for DeviceKit-power.<ref name="udisks">{{cite web | url=https://lists.freedesktop.org/archives/devkit-devel/2009-December/000567.html | title=DeviceKit-disks renamed to udisks | author=David Zeuthen | date=2009-12-01 | accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref>
== Future == According to DeviceKit devel mailing list, DeviceKit is getting merged with <tt>udev-extra</tt> and the existing DeviceKit programs such as [[DeviceKit-disks]] and [[DeviceKit-power]] will be switched over to use <tt>libudev</tt>.<ref name="udisks"/><ref>{{cite web | url=https://lists.freedesktop.org/archives/devkit-devel/2009-April/000140.html | title=udev rules files | author=Kay Sievers | date=2009-04-26 | accessdate=2017-01-15}}</ref>
